						<h2>History</h2>
						 Originally, Mboro was nothing more than a tiny Peul hamlet. It was part of the Cayor Kingdom which 
						 split from the Djolof empire in 1549. The Cayor Kingdom was ruled by Wolof Damels, of whom Lat Dior was the last and most 
						 famous.It operated under a cast system in which Damels were selected by a council representative of people from all 
						 walks of life.<br>
						 In the late 14<sup>th</sup> century, Damels started trading with Europeans who were then allowed to build trade posts. Over the years, they agreed to pay annual taxes to the Damel until 
						 the 19<sup>th</sup> century when the colonization process began.
						 In 1862, Pinet Laprade, Faidherbe's successor as Governor of Senegal with his troops, discovered the hamlet of Mboro on their way from Saint Louis to Dakar. He instantly saw it's huge agricultural potential.
						 Later on, the French Colonial Administration in West Africa decided to start in the region, a vegetables and fruit production spot. Offering land, seeds and farming machinery, they encouraged folks from all corners of the country to come to settle there. 
						 Hence the heterogeneous feature of Mboro's today population. It's a direct legacy of that historic move and mirrors the diverse indigenous who volunteered to populate it in the first place.<br> 
						 <a href="http://lyceemboro.edu.sn/2017/12/22/presentation-de-mboro/" target="_blank"><span style="font-size:small">click to see. mboro high school / history of Mboro (French).</span> </a>
